04954nam a22005295i 9780773562264DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19921992xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735622647 a10.1515/97807735622642doi  a(DE-B1597)655098  a(OCoLC)1064747053  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHJ2614.5bG56 1992eb 7aBUS0640002bisacsh04a336.22/09421 aGinter, Donald E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMeasure of Wealth :bThe English Land Tax in Historical Analysis /cDonald E. Ginter. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1992] 4c©1992  a1 online resource (744 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tList of Tables -- tList of Maps -- tList of Appendices -- tAbbreviations -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tThe Role of the Land Tax in Historical Analysis -- tInterpreting the Structure of the Land Tax Duplicates -- tMinor Problems -- tMajor Problems -- tRoman Catholic Double Assessment -- tConverting Tax Values to Acres -- tThe Mechanisms and Terminology of Rating -- tThe Mechanisms and Terminology of Rating -- tThe Incidence and Level of Revaluation -- tThe Impact of Redemption -- tThe Equitability of Assessments within Townships -- tThe Explanation of Inequalities -- tThe Regional and National Distribution of the Land Tax Burden -- tThe National Distribution of the Land Tax Burden: The Traditional Evidence -- tValuational Rent and Local Poundage Rates in the North Riding of Yorkshire c. 1830 -- tA Met hod for Estimating Inequalities in the Regional and National Distribution of the Land Tax: Finding a Maximum Valuation Series -- tTesting the Maximum Series for Comparability: Spatial Distribution Patterns in the North, East, and West Ridings of Yorkshire -- tThe National Distribution of the Land Tax Burden: New Estimates for 1815 -- tConclusions -- tA New Look at the Historiography of Land Tax Studies -- tMaps -- tAppendices -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aGinter focuses on the years 1780 to 1832, a period for which many land tax records survive and precisely when modern forms of political organization began to emerge and when industrialization and enclosure are thought to have altered the fabric of society and the economy. Through an examination of more than 5,000 parishes in fifteen historical counties -- approximately one-third of England -- he shows that inequalities in the burden of national taxation were far greater than anyone has estimated. Having researched both local and national taxation procedures, he reveals that, on the eve of the nineteenth-century "Revolution in Government," the tenantry and yeomanry were administratively far more independent of parliamentary statute and of their local gentry and magistracy than has previously been suggested. Drawing on evidence from the three ridings of Yorkshire, he discloses other problems associated with the land tax duplicates. While Ginter argues that the land tax duplicates are wholly inadequate for the study of the fortunes of the small yeoman and that the literature on this subject must be fundamentally reconsidered, he reveals a method which can reliably exploit the land tax duplicates as a systemic documentation. He contends that the full potential for studies based centrally on the land tax has scarcely begun to be explored.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPropriété immobilièrexImpôtsxHistoirexAngleterrexEngland. 0aReal property taxxHistoryxEngland. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Taxation / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z